<p></p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Plot">Plot</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=In_the_Heat_of_the_Night_(film)&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1" title="Edit section: Plot">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<p>Philip Colbert, a wealthy entrepreneur and industrialist from <a href="/wiki/Chicago" title="Chicago">Chicago</a> who is planning to build a factory for his company in Sparta, Mississippi, is found murdered. White Police Chief Bill Gillespie seeking quick resolution to the mystery orders his officers to thoroughly search the cityâs nearly deserted streets and closed businesses for anyone who might have seen or heard something or who is suspiciously outside in the middle of the night, in a small town where everyone goes to bed at sunset. This search, by Officer Sam Wood, discovers an African-American northerner <a href="/wiki/Virgil_Tibbs" title="Virgil Tibbs">Virgil Tibbs</a> in the waiting room of the Sparta train station. The waiting room is open but unstaffed as the station is closed at that hour. Tibbs is only passing through town, waiting to complete his change in trains (by way of an unfamiliar but valid connection) and is bound for <a href="/wiki/Memphis,_Tennessee" title="Memphis, Tennessee">Memphis, Tennessee</a>. He's picked up at the train station and has a substantial amount of cash in his wallet. Gillespie, prejudiced against blacks, jumps to the conclusion that he has his culprit but is embarrassed to learn that Tibbs is an experienced police officer from <a href="/wiki/Philadelphia" title="Philadelphia">Philadelphia</a>, and a recognized homicide detective of some renown who is simply passing through Sparta, literally changing trains, after visiting his mother. After the racist treatment that he receives Tibbs wants nothing more than to leave as quickly as possible but his own chief, after questioning whether Tibbs himself is prejudiced, has him stay and offer his expertise. Leslie Colbert, the victim's widow, already frustrated by the ineptitude of the local police is impressed by Tibbs' expertise when he clears another wrongly accused suspect whom Gillespie has arrested on circumstantial evidence. She threatens to stop construction on the much needed factory unless Tibbs leads the investigation. Unwilling to accept help but under orders from the town's mayor, Gillespie talks a reluctant Tibbs into working on the case.</p>
<p>Despite the rocky start to their relationship the two policemen are compelled to respect each other as they are forced to work together to solve the crime. Tibbs initially suspects wealthy plantation owner Eric Endicott, a racist who publicly opposed the new factory, as the early clues point to Colbert's visit to Endicott's plantation earlier that evening. When Tibbs attempts to interrogate Endicott about Colbert Endicott slaps him in the face but Tibbs slaps him back which leads to Endicott sending a gang of hooligans after Tibbs. Gillespie rescues him from the fight and orders him to leave town for his own safety but Tibbs refuses to leave until he has solved the case.</p>
<p>Tibbs asks Officer Wood, the officer who discovered the body, to retrace his movements at the same time when he was on roving patrol in Sparta on the night of the murder. Tibbs and Gillespie accompany Wood on his patrol route, stopping at a diner (where Wood took his mid-shift break). The counterman, Ralph Henshaw, refuses to serve Tibbs. Henshaw also observes Gillespie and Tibbs investigating the murder. After they leave the diner, still retracing Wood's movements on the night of the murder, Tibbs observes that Wood is deliberately changing his patrol route to bypass the house where 16 year-old Delores Purdy parades around in the nude at night, to taunt the suitor (Officer Wood) that she's led on. Tibbs knows all of this because of his talking with a cellmate when briefly under arrest in Gillespie's jail. Gillespie starts suspecting Wood of the crime because of his unexplained attempt to hide the truth of his whereabouts when on patrol. Tibbs later tells Gillespie he knows why Sam has changed his route but will not disclose the reason to Gillespie.</p>
<p>However, when Gillespie discovers that Wood made a sizable deposit into his bank account the day after the murder (which Wood claims is gambling winnings) and Lloyd Purdy, a local, files charges against Wood for getting his 16-year-old sister Delores pregnant, Gillespie arrests Wood for the murder despite Tibbs's protests. Purdy is insulted that Tibbs, a black man, was present for his sister's interrogation about her sexual encounter with Wood, and he gathers a mob to get his revenge on Tibbs.</p>
<p>Tibbs is able to clear Wood in two ways. First, he found Colbert's blood in the back seat of his own car. This confirmed what Tibbs had always suspected from his first examination of Colbert's body. Colbert was killed earlier than initially thought, before Officer Wood began his roving patrol. Once killed, Colbert's body was placed in the back seat of his car and driven from where the killing took place to where the body was dropped. Therefore, Sam Wood "... couldn't have driven two cars ..." at the same time, his police patrol car and the victim's car. Tibbs' roving search of Sparta finds the original murder scene where the probable murder weapon (a wooden surveying stake, used as a club) is of the same type of wood as the splinters which were found embedded in Colbert's scalp and skull. Tibbs also admits that he knew immediately that Wood changed his route not to hide the fact that he was a murderer but that he was a "<a href="/wiki/Voyeurism" title="Voyeurism">peeping Tom</a>" and declined to publicly reveal this in order to spare Wood the embarrassment.</p>
<p>When Lloyd Purdy files charges against Wood for statutory rape of his 16 year-old baby-sister Tibbs realizes Delores Purdy (or Delores and her accomplice) have decided to falsely provide Officer Wood with a motive for murdering Philip Colbert for money; that the money was needed so that Wood could pay for Delores to get an abortion. But Tibbs knows that while that motive of murder for money might be true, it wasn't because Sam Wood got Delores Purdy pregnant. Someone else got her pregnant and that someone else, knowing that Wood was under suspicion for Colbert's death, might have tried to frame Wood for the crime. So Tibbs tracks down a local high priced back-room abortionist who reveals that someone has paid well for Delores to have an abortion. When Delores arrives, Tibbs pursues her outside where he is confronted by the murderer, Henshaw. Purdy's mob tracks down Tibbs at this moment and he is being held at gunpoint when he proves to Purdy that it was Henshaw, not Wood, who got Delores pregnant, and that Henshaw has given his little sister an unheard of sum of money for the abortion. When Purdy sees the hundreds of dollars in Delores' purse, he knows its Ralph Henshaw who's turned his little sister into a "field slut". Henshaw shoots Purdy dead before being disarmed by Tibbs. Henshaw is arrested and confesses to the murder of Colbert.</p>
<p>Henshaw tells Gillespie that he left his trailer on foot, planning to walk to Lloyd Purdy's house to see Delores on the way to work. Lloyd Purdy worked nights and would not be coming home unexpectedly. When he left the Purdy home, Henshaw did so early enough so that he could walk to the roadside diner and arrive in time to relieve the evening counter-man and begin the midnight shift. Philip Colbert was driving back to his hotel from his meeting with Endicott when he saw Henshaw walking along the road. As an out-of-town businessman who had used the diner many times and who knew the workers there, he picked up Henshaw with the intent of dropping him off at the diner, thus saving him the time and fatigue of walking.</p>
<p>As he would arrive at work early, and was in no hurry to do so, Henshaw readily agreed to let Colbert show him the site of the new factory he was having built. At the construction site Henshaw had attempted to rob Colbert to gain money to pay for Delores's abortion but accidentally killed him.</p>
<p>His job done, Tibbs finally boards the <a href="/wiki/Gulf,_Mobile_%26_Ohio" title="Gulf, Mobile &amp; Ohio" class="mw-redirect">Gulf, Mobile &amp; Ohio</a> train out of town, regarded by a now respectful Gillespie.</p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Cast">Cast</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=In_the_Heat_of_the_Night_(film)&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2" title="Edit section: Cast">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<div class="div-col columns column-count column-count-2" style="-moz-column-count: 2; -webkit-column-count: 2; column-count: 2;">
<ul>
<li><a href="/wiki/Sidney_Poitier" title="Sidney Poitier">Sidney Poitier</a> as Detective <a href="/wiki/Virgil_Tibbs" title="Virgil Tibbs">Virgil Tibbs</a></li>
